Nigerian equities market suffered its biggest weekly loss since April 2019 by 4.28 per cent with investors exiting on increasing regulatory risk in the banking sector, a slump in oil prices, and as the first case of the Coronavirus (COVID-19) was reported in the country. Consequently, the benchmark index, All-Share Index declined by 1,172.16 points or 4.28 per cent week-on-week (W-o-W) to close at 26,216.46 points. Similarly, market capitalisation value declined by N611 billion to close for the week at NN13.658 trillion. Performance across sectors was unimpressive W-o-W. Sell pressures in FBN Holdings, Wema Bank and Ecobank Transnational Corporation (ETI) compelled the sharpest loss in the Banking index as the index shed 11.79 per cent. The Insurance and Consumer Goods indices dipped 8.22 per cent and 3.84 per cent respectively owing to price declines in Aiico Insurance and Nigerian Breweries, while the loss in Oando dragged the Oil & Gas index down by 2.14 per cent. On the flip side, the Industrial Goods index gained by 1.08 per cent due to price appreciation in BUA Cement. Market breadth for the week was negative as six equities appreciated in price, 58 equities depreciated in price, while 99 equities remained unchanged. Law Union and Rock Insurance led the gainers table by 23.29 per cent to close at 90 kobo, per share. May & Baker Nigeria followed with a gain of 7.69 per cent to close at N1.96, while Ekocorp Plc went up by 5.77 per cent to close to N5.50, per share. On the other side, Red Star Express led the decliners table by 26.97 per cent to close at N3.25, per share. Aiico Insurance followed with a loss of 23.76 per cent to close at 77 kobo and NPF Microfinance Bank declined by 23.39 per cent to close at 95 kobo, per share. Overall, a total turnover of 1.547 billion shares worth N24.263 billion in 21,646 deals were traded last week by investors on the floor of the Exchange, in contrast to a total of 1.499 billion shares valued at N17.907 billion that exchanged hands previous week in 18,515 deals. In the new week, analysts at Cowry Asset Management Limited expected a mix of profit taking and bargain hunting activities as share prices tumble to attractive levels amid expectations of further corporate announcements. Also analysts at GTI Securities Limited expected market jitters to remain this  trading week as more investors seeks safe haven for their asset, over the expected negative impact of Covid-19 entrance in Nigeria. Cordros Capital Limited said “Amidst continued weak market sentiments, we advise investors to trade cautiously, taking positions in fundamentally justified stocks.” 